I"E<p>The residue at infinity is a useful quantity to calculate for certain integrals which have many singularities within a certain region. The residue at infinity allows one to calculate a single residue to find the value of the integral instead of many and summing them up.</p>

<table>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td>Suppose we have the Laurent expansion of a function $f(z)$, which is valid outside of a certain region $</td>
      <td>z</td>
      <td>&gt; R$. Thus we express it as</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

\[f(z) \sim \frac{a_{-1}}{z} + \frac{a_{-2}}{z^2} + \cdots\]
